SIMPLE: impost
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Impost
<hw>Im"post</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF.
<ets>impost</ets>, F. <ets>impot</ets>, LL. <ets>impostus</ets>, fr. L.
<ets>impostus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>imponere</ets> to impose. See
<er>Impone</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>That which is imposed or
levied; a tax, tribute, or duty; especially, a duty or tax laid by
government on goods imported into a country.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Even the ship money . . . Johnson could not pronounce to have been
an unconstitutional <qex>impost</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>The top member of a pillar, pier,
wall, etc., upon which the weight of an arch rests.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The impost is called <xex>continuous</xex>, if the
moldings of the arch or architrave run down the jamb or pier without a
break.</note></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Tribute; excise; custom; duty; tax.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Imposthumate</ent>⟦br⟧
